ce:section.ce:para:
R6G as the model dye is selected to explore the photocatalytic activity of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs. The photocatalytic activity of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs with different masses is first investigated and the most appropriate amount used for the photodegradation of R6G is 50 mg (Figure S11). Meanwhile, the photocatalytic activity of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs increases significantly with the increase of H2O2 concentration (Figure S12). Furthermore, we investigate the role of gadolinium in photocatalysis. Results (Fig. 3c) show that R6G is hardly degraded under the action of S-MNs in the white light, indicating that gadolinium micro-networks do not have the photocatalytic capacity because of the rapid electron and hole recombination. Therefore, the function of gadolinium is to form gadolinium micro-networks with strong fluorescence with citric acid [33]. P-MNs in Cu2-xSe/P-MNs composites, mainly as electron donors, transfer electrons generated by light excitation to Cu2-xSe. The intimate interface between two components of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs hybrid photocatalyst can effectively improve the separation of photogenerated electron–hole pairs, thus causing the high photocatalysis activity. Meanwhile, we also investigate the effect of Cu2-xSe on the degradation of R6G dye. Because of the peroxidase-like activity [41], Cu2-xSe solution has a certain catalytic ability for dyes degradation. The catalytic effect of Cu2-xSe on R6G dyes can be further improved under the action of white light because of the photothermal effect [40]. Meanwhile, Cu2-xSe/P-MNs can also catalyze the degradation of dyes in the dark, which should be attributed to the peroxidase-like activity of Cu2-xSe. But the catalytic activity of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs in the dark is obviously lower than that of pure Cu2-xSe solution (0.2 mg/mL, 5 mL), suggesting that Cu2-xSe accounts for a small proportion (<2%) in the Cu2-xSe/P-MNs and has a small contact area with R6G dyes due to being wrapped by P-MNs. While Cu2-xSe/P-MNs in the white light show very high catalytic activity. Under optimum conditions, the R6G can be rapidly photodegraded. Within 5 min, the degradation efficiency reaches more than 65% and 95% in 10 min. Finally, the degradation efficiency of R6G can be as high as 99% when the reaction time is 15 min. The R6G dyes will not be mineralized in the process of photocatalysis, and the orange dye solution becomes a transparent solution after photocatalysis (Figure S13). Meanwhile, the degradation kinetics of R6G under white light irradiation follows a pseudo-first-order kinetics plot. Based on the calculated rate constants (Fig. 3d), the degradation rate of R6G using Cu2-xSe/P-MNs can be up to 0.33 min−1, which is significantly higher than other common photocatalysts (
                        Table 1

                        ). It should be pointed out that H2O2 does not exist in all other catalytic systems in Table 1, which may be the reason why their catalytic activities are limited. Compared with other photocatalysts, the facile large-scale synthesis (gram scale), low-power white light photocatalysis (20 W), high photocatalytic rate (0.33 min−1), and fast degradation time (15 min) make Cu2-xSe/P-MNs have good application prospects in photocatalytic applications. Meanwhile, the stability of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs catalyst is also further studied. SEM image (Figure S14) clearly shows that Cu2-xSe/P-MNs, after the catalysis of R6G dyes, still maintain a complete morphology. Moreover, the catalytic behavior also does not affect the crystal structure of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs (Figure S15). The photodegradation efficiency can still be maintained at 93% after five cycles of photocatalysis (Figure S16), suggesting that Cu2-xSe/P-MNs photocatalysts have high stability and repeatability.

Therefore, the efficient photocatalytic activity of R6G dye using Cu2-xSe/P-MNs is mainly attributed to the ‘three channels’ catalytic path (Scheme 1

                        ). In short, Cu2-xSe/P-MN can produce photoexcited e− and h+ in white light (Fig. 4d). Then photogenerated e− can be effectively transferred to Cu2-xSe to further catalyze H2O2 to produce ⋅OH, which catalyzes the degradation of dyes (channel 1). Meanwhile, the photogenerated h+ can also catalyze H2O2 to produce O2
                        •−, which catalyzes the photodegradation of dyes (channel 2). Moreover, h+ can also directly oxidize R6G dyes because of its good oxidation capacity (channel 3). Meanwhile, Cu2-xSe can also produce highly reactive oxygen (such as ⋅OH) under the condition of light irradiation because of the peroxidase-like activity and the photothermal effect (Fig. 4d) [49]. Therefore, the high catalytic activity of Cu2-xSe/P-MNs in white light mainly comes from the white light-driven photocatalytic activity producing highly reactive oxygen because of the strong separation of electrons and holes in Cu2-xSe/P-MNs, followed by the peroxidase-like activity and the photothermal effect of Cu2-xSe.
